<subSubSection lastPageId="276" lastPageNumber="277" pageId="275" pageNumber="276" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="275" pageNumber="276">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="276" lastPageNumber="277" pageId="275" pageNumber="276">
To our knowledge, species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara, 2016" authorityName="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Austrosolieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrosolieria" order="Diptera" pageId="275" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Austrosolieria</taxonomicName>
are not easily confused with those of any other Afrotropical genus. However, the habitus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara, 2016" authorityName="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Austrosolieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrosolieria" order="Diptera" pageId="275" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Austrosolieria</taxonomicName>
species and the combination of a wide frons, bare prosternum, three postsutural dorsocentral setae, 
<pageBreakToken pageId="276" pageNumber="277" start="start">two</pageBreakToken>
strong marginal scutellar setae (subapical and basal), hind tibia with short and weak preapical posteroventral seta, and costal spine well developed, are reminiscent of the Palaearctic genera 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Solieria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Solieria" order="Diptera" pageId="276" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Solieria</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Bithia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bithia" order="Diptera" pageId="276" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bithia</taxonomicName>
Robineau-Desvoidy, and, in part, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Clausicella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Clausicella" order="Diptera" pageId="276" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Clausicella</taxonomicName>
Rondani. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara, 2016" authorityName="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Austrosolieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrosolieria" order="Diptera" pageId="276" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Austrosolieria</taxonomicName>
differs from these by having the lower facial margin not protruding and not visible in lateral view, fore tibia with preapical anteroventral seta distinctly longer than preapical dorsal seta, and postpedicel more or less sharply pointed at apex in male. We have determined that the two new species described below do not fit within the limits of an existing tachinid genus and propose for them the new genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara, 2016" authorityName="Cerretti &amp; O'Hara" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Austrosolieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrosolieria" order="Diptera" pageId="276" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Austrosolieria</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
